<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Patten's approach supported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA'S ATTEMPTS to undermine the position of Mr Chris Patten, the governor
of Hong Kong, were bluntly repudiated by Mr John Major, the prime minister,
yesterday.
He affirmed Britain's readiness for further talks with China without
preconditions, but told the Commons the government backed Mr Patten, who has
proposed democratic elections in the colony.
He said Mr Patten had acted 'sensitively, resolutely and correctly', and
assured MPs that Britain would continue to make this clear to China, which
is due to regain Hong Kong in 1997.
</TEXT>
