<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Row looms on public-sector pay
limits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY is set to fight calls from Whitehall spending ministers for the
planned extension into next year of a tough squeeze on public-sector pay to
be imposed again through a formal and published pay ceiling.
Whitehall officials and senior ministers indicated yesterday that the
Treasury's spending plans for 1994-95 and 1995-96 would allow for an
increase in the public-sector wage bill of at most 2 per cent next year.
Some ministers believe that figure might come down towards zero in the next
few months as departments take on new spending commitments. The spending
ministers are arguing privately that the pay squeeze will be impossible to
enforce without a formal limit applying to all public-sector workers. But Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, plans to resist calls from colleagues in the
main spending departments for the present published 1.5 per cent pay ceiling
to be rolled over into 1994-95.
Mr Lamont will argue during this summer's public spending negotiations that
an unpublished Treasury ceiling for the overall wage bill should be met
through informal limits for each of the main departments. That would put the
onus on each department to strike a balance between wage re-straint, cuts in
capital programmes and job losses in areas such as the National Health
Service, schools, the police and the fire service.
The chancellor's stance appears to have set the stage for a political row
with some of his colleagues.
Last year spending ministers on the powerful EDX public expenditure cabinet
committee, charged with thrashing out the allocation of available funds,
pushed for the 1.5 per cent ceiling to be imposed for two years. Mr Lamont
succeeded then in restricting it to one year, but some of his colleagues are
arguing that the pressures on pay have intensified since that deal was
struck .
This week's Budget showed that Whitehall budgets in 1994-95 will be 0.25 per
cent lower in real terms than in the financial year which starts next month.
Unions representing public-sector workers reacted angrily to suggestions
that the government might set a pay ceiling for a second year.
Nalgo, the local government union, said: 'The government is storing up
enormous industrial problems for itself. 'Attempts to make public-sector
workers pay for the government's incompetent economic performance this year,
next year or any other year will not be tolerated.'
The Royal College of Nursing said the prime minister had made a clear
commitment to its pay review body to recommend pay levels in 1993-94. 'We
shall be holding him to that,' it said.
</TEXT>
