<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Budget package will help only 'one
in 30' on dole
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will spend less than Pounds 1 extra a week on each of
Britain's unemployed as a result of the new measures in Tuesday's Budget,
Labour said yesterday.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, told MPs the new package would
help just one in 30 of those in Britain's dole queues.
He said that since Mr John Major's only Budget three years ago unemployment
had risen by 87 per cent and 9.5m people had experienced the pain of being
out of work. Unemployment was 'ruining the lives of 3m people and their
families and shattering the economy'.
In a wide-ranging dissection of the government's new proposals, Mr Dobson
nonetheless welcomed 'without reservation' yesterday's 22,000 fall in the
seasonally adjusted monthly unemployment figures.
Though the decline could be a freak, it was 'undoubtedly the only piece of
good news on unemployment for three years.
'If this is the start of a trend, it had better be an accelerating one
because at 22,000 a month it will take eleven years before all people out of
work are in work.'
On the specific steps outlined on Tuesday, Mr Dobson gave a guarded welcome
to the four Workstart pilot areas. These represent the government's first
acceptance of the principle of job subsidies to employers who take on the
unemployed.
But he said the great danger of the proposition was that employers might
simply substitute existing workers with those carrying the subsidy.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, who opened yesterday's debate,
was challenged by one of her own backbenchers on why Workstart - which will
initially involve 1,000 of those unemployed for more than two years at a
cost of Pounds 2.6m - did not go further.
Questioned by Labour on why the subsidy to employers had been pegged at
Pounds 60 a week, Mrs Shephard said a flat rate was easier to administer.
She said Tuesday's measures, costed at a net Pounds 125m, should be seen in
the context of the proposals announced in last year's Autumn Statement.
Welcoming the fall in the unemployment figures, she said it would help to
stimulate business confidence, especially as it had come so early in the
recovery cycle.
The number of unemployed people placed into new jobs by the Employment
Service was up on last year, while the number of people becoming newly
unemployed was down.
</TEXT>
