<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Usdaw chiefs back reforms by Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAMPAIGN in the Labour party to introduce a one-member-one-vote (Omov)
system for the selection of parliamentary candidates achieved a significant
breakthrough when leaders of the shopworkers' union Usdaw came out in
favour.
This arrangement would replace the present system in which unions exercise a
direct vote in candidate selection through local electoral colleges
alongside individual members.
Usdaw's executive will recommend the change at the union's annual conference
in April. If carried, it will strengthen the chances of success for the
reform at Labour's conference in the autumn.
The change of union policy on reform will please Mr John Smith, the Labour
leader, who also favours the reform and in the next few months will increase
pressure on other unions to support it. 'The outcome on Omov may now be too
close to call,' said one union official.
It is estimated that more than 1.5m union votes are committed to the new
system. It will be opposed by the Transport and General Workers, the
General, Municipal and Boilermakers and the Public Employees, which together
account formore than 2m votes.
The union block vote will fall from 89 per cent to 70 per cent at this
year's Labour conference, however, and the constituency parties are expected
to back the system.
