<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Union supports selection reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAMPAIGN in the Labour party to introduce one member one vote (OMOV) for
the selection of parliamentary candidates achieved a significant
breakthrough when leaders of the Shopworkers' union Usdaw came out in favour
of the reform.
This would replace the present system, where unions exercise a direct vote
in candidate selection through local electoral colleges alongside individual
members.
Usdaw's executive will recommend the change at the union's annual conference
in April. If this is carried it will strengthen the chances of success for
OMOV at Labour's conference in the autumn.
The change of union policy on OMOV will please Labour leader John Smith, who
also favours the reform and will increase the pressure on other unions over
the next few months to support it. 'The outcome on OMOV may now be too close
to call,' said one union official.
It is estimated that more than 1.5m union votes are committed to OMOV. It
will be opposed by the Transport and General Workers, the General, Municipal
and Boilermakers and the Public Employees who make up more than 2m votes.
The union block vote falls from 89 per cent to 70 per cent at this year's
Labour conference, however, and the constituency parties - with increased
representation - are expected to back OMOV.
USDAW said it would continue to back the use of an electoral college for the
election of the leader and deputy, but would back a cut in the union
proportion of the college from 40 per cent to 33 per cent.
It also favours reducing the union vote to party conference from 70 per cent
to 50 per cent over the next few years as individual membership grows.
Mr Bill Morris, the TGWU's general secretary, warned last night that if
Labour 'cuts itself adrift from the unions, it cuts itself adrift from its
most solid base of support.'
He added the current debate over the relationship between the unions and
Labour was 'overheated' and in danger of plunging the party into
'unnecessary, internal preoccupations.'
</TEXT>
