<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Jobless fall baffles Whitehall: Drop in unemployment may
signal recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMISTS and statis-ticians struggled yesterday to explain last month's
sharp drop in unemployment. One baffled official confessed the figures were
checked twice, such was the surprise at the Department of Employment.
Most analysts said it was too early to judge whether the seasonally adjusted
fall of 22,000 represented a turnaround or whether it was a statistical
quirk. However, the official figures highlighted encouraging trends.
The Department of Employment said the February fall was driven by a drop in
the number of people registering for unemployment benefit. About 370,000
people joined the claimant count last month, 19,500 fewer than in the same
month last year. Outflows from the count were 391,200, over 33,000 more than
in February last year. Some of the outflows would have left the count to
join government employment schemes. The number of people involved in
Employment Training, for example, rose 5,000 in February compared with
January.
There was no regional explanation for the reduction in unemployment. The
good news was spread fairly evenly across the country with the jobless total
falling in all regions except Greater London, northern England and Northern
Ireland. Unemployment in the south-east, one of the regions worst hit by the
recession, fell by a seasonally-adjusted 5,700 in February compared with
January. But in Greater London it rose 800 on the month. In the north the
number of people out of work and claiming benefit rose by 600 and in
Northern Ireland by 200.
Some regions experienced their first drop in unemployment for three years,
noticeably East Anglia where it fell by 1,200 and the west Midlands where it
dropped 2,400. East Anglia and the south-west had the biggest percentage
falls in unemployment.
February's sharp overall drop has left in question the trend growth rate in
unemployment. February's fall cut sharply the underlying rate of increase as
measured by the three-month on three-month comparison. In the three months
to the end of February the jobless total rose by 19,500 compared with 41,800
in the three months to the end of January. February's fall was consistent
with a sharp pick-up in vacancies at Jobcentres, about a third of all
vacancies in the economy. These rose by a seasonally adjusted 17,600 in
February after falling by 4,400 in January, although the department warned
that the figures were subject to revision because of software problems.
Economists also pointed to a slowdown in the rate at which the level of
overall employment is falling. The workforce in employment dropped 85,000 in
the fourth quarter to 24.9bn, the smallest fall since the first quarter of
last year.
In manufacturing the number of people employed was estimated to have fallen
by 13,000 in January to 4.2bn. This was the smallest fall since May last
year. In the service industries the number of individuals in employment rose
by 51,000 in the fourth quarter after falling 254,000 in the third quarter.
The number of hours worked over time also pointed towards a pick-up in
activity. In January there were 9.45m overtime hours worked compared with
8.31m in December.
The Department of Employment issued the results of its quarterly labour
force survey yesterday. This measures unemployment through a household
survey rather than by simply adding up the number of people claiming
unemployment benefit. It showed that in the three months to the end of
November, unemployment was 2.8m. This was 66,000 more than the average
monthly number of unemployed recorded by the claimant count.
</TEXT>
