<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Overseas orders boost engineering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VALUE of international construction contracts involving British
consulting engineers jumped by more than 40 per cent from Pounds 41.98bn to
Pounds 60.06bn last year according to figures published yesterday.
Consulting engineers are estimated to have contributed Pounds 625m to
Britain's invisible earnings in 1992 - almost 39 per cent more than the
Pounds 450m earned in 1991.
The figures, published by the Association of Consulting Engineers, do not
include any contribution from British contractors or building material
producers working on international projects.
The increase in international orders was in part due to several large
transport and energy projects mostly in the Far East.
As a result the capital value of new projects for which British consultants
won contracts more than doubled to Pounds 27.75bn. More than a third of this
arose from the Pounds 10bn Bangkok Elevated Transport System in which Ove
Arup is involved.
British consultants have also been working on a Pounds 2.7bn landfill
project in Hong Kong which is part of the transport infrastructure of the
new Chep Lap Kok airport. Contracts were also won last year on several large
power station projects in China.
Mr Povl Ahm, chairman of the association, said that the level of
international construction orders from China was increasing. He was
concerned that Britain should not lose a share of this work because of
problems over Hong Kong.
But he added that there was no sign of significant recovery in world
construction orders outside the Far East. The capital value of Far Eastern
projects involving British consultants rose from Pounds 11.85bn to Pounds
28.85bn last year.
</TEXT>
