<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / OFT life insurance proposals: Insurers attack 'unfair'
disclosure demands - Treasury wants agreement soon, Business may shift from
life houses, Annual statements for policyholders urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMANDS from the Office of Fair Trading for life insurance sales agents to
tell prospective clients much more about costs were attacked by many figures
in the industry.
Mr Brian Richardson, chairman of the Association of British Insurers' life
council, yesterday expressed 'regret and disappointment'. But Mr Tony Baker,
public affairs director at the association, described the new proposals as
'unnecessary and unfair' and said that some of them were likely to
discourage sales of new products. The association's objections focus on two
main elements of the Office of Fair Trading report. The first is its
suggestion that independent financial advisers should be required to
disclose their commissions in cash terms to prospective customers. The
second is its suggestion that customers should be told what the value of
their policy would be in each year if it is surrendered before maturity.
'It would serve to put some people off buying that product,' Mr Baker said.
'It would have an unnecessary and unfair effect on sales.'
Ms Julia Leisching, regulatory consultant to the financial services
industry, argued that consumers would be unable to understand tables of such
complexity.
Independent financial advisers (IFAs) reacted furiously to the report's call
for commission disclosure, although the other proposals met with broad
approval.
Mr Kenneth Davy, president of the Life Insurance Association, a trade body
for both independent and tied intermediaries, condemned the proposals for
commission disclosure as 'quite ridiculous'. He said: 'It will be extremely
detrimental for the IFA sector. The banks and building societies will be
delighted because they will be able to give essentially biased advice. The
OFT's own research provides no compelling evidence for commission
disclosure.'
His views were echoed by Ms Joanne Hindle, chief executive officer of IFA
Promotion, which promotes the use of independent advisers. She described the
pursuit of commission disclosure as 'misguided'.
She added: 'It is in everyone's best interest that full commission
disclosure is held in abeyance. Should the OFT recommendation be accepted by
the Treasury, there is a very real danger that we will see the level playing
field tilt away from the IFA sector, making it all too easy for a tied agent
to claim that he or she is paid less commission for selling a product than
an IFA.'
There were some dissident voices. Mr Tony Shepherd, a fee-charging
independent financial adviser and chairman of the Institute of Financial
Planning, welcomed all the report. He said: 'I personally am in favour of
commission disclosure because I think commission is the principal cause of
malpractice in the insurance industry.'
Fimbra, the self-regulatory body for independent financial advisers
yesterday said it would try to convince the Treasury that IFA commission
disclosure is inappropriate.
Meanwhile, industry analysts say that the proposed rule allowing low-cost
sales outlets to price their products more cheaply may well hasten the rise
of so-called bancassurance. Banks and building societies which act as the
'tied' sales outlets for a single insurance company have lower costs and
consequently could, if current rules allowed, try to compete on price. Until
now, regulators have forbidden this but the OFT argues that rule is
anti-competitive.
</TEXT>
