<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / OFT life insurance proposals: Early changes to rules
unlikely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY new rules for the life insurance industry are likely to be a long way
off even though the Office of Fair Trading has given its views about
encouraging competition.
Moreover, recent pronouncements from the Treasury, the Securities and
Investments Board and the insurance industry suggest there is far more
willingness by all parties to introduce a better disclosure regime.
The OFT first sought tougher disclosure rules for life insurance products in
1989 and yesterday's report reflects its comments on a two-year exercise
involving the industry and SIB.
Officially the report must be presented to the Treasury, which will then
decide if it agrees with the OFT's conclusions. The Treasury said: 'We must
decide first whether the current rules are seriously anti-competitive and if
so, are they enough so that investor protection is seriously impaired.'
If the Treasury decides they are anti-competitive, it can direct SIB to
draft a new set of disclosure rules aimed at meeting the OFT's objections.
Yesterday SIB said it would be speaking with the self-regulatory bodies
about formalising those parts of its proposed disclosure regime that the OFT
has accepted as suitable for promoting competition. Those rules include
disclosure of how many pence per pound each company's total expenses will
reduce final pay-outs by, and rules covering disclosure of each sales
agent's status.
The Association of British Insurers and other industry groups are preparing
to lobby strongly for the Treasury to reject the OFT report.
The Treasury is not inviting industry comment and has said it wishes to make
a decision as quickly as possible. 'We are quite willing to listen to
representations from all interested parties,' it said. 'But obviously the
Treasury wishes to make its own assessments.'
Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, has publicly called
for improved investor protection in the industry.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said he was hopeful
that the industry would accept the proposed new regime. 'I do believe that
there is a new feeling in the industry,' he said. 'It is starting to feel
that the public is losing confidence in the product.'
</TEXT>
