<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Daf buy-out decision is likely in two weeks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE future of the management buy-out bid for the Leyland Daf plant in
Birmingham is likely to be settled within the next fortnight.
Its chances of success have been improved by the decision on Wednesday of
3i, the venture capital group, to advance equity finance.
Mr Ken Ogilvy, a partner at Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm, said
yesterday that detailed cashflow projections for the next six months of the
plant's operations were being prepared for presentation next week to the
credit committees of clearing banks and finance houses.
Coopers is trying to pull together a finance package for the buy-out team
led by Mr Allan Amey.
Banks and finance houses are needed by the management buy-out team to
provide the debt element of the financing package, which will also involve
the public sector.
The Department of Trade and Industry is understood to have been carrying out
its procedures of 'due diligence' yesterday on an application by the
management team for regional selective assistance.
This is a subsidy available to Leyland Daf under the terms of the Industrial
Development Act 1982 to provide funds for modernisation in order to
safeguard employment.
The speed with which the DTI has been processing the application underlines
the government's desire to keep open a plant in an area of high
unemployment.
If the joint receiver, Mr Murdoch McKillop of Arthur Andersen, the
accountancy firm, closes the plant it is unlikely to reopen.
Orders for Leyland Daf vans tail away from mid April because of uncertainty
about the future.
Mr Ogilvy said: 'Much beyond that the order book looks pretty poor.' Dealers
have been holding back from placing firm orders until the outcome of the
buyout bid is clear.
Mr Ogilvy said: 'We will not be in a position to strike a deal with the
receiver for another week or so.' The attitude of the banks was crucial, but
he felt that 3i's decision had put down a marker. 'It starts to focus
everybody's mind that what might be possible is possible.'
Mr Chris Rowlands, the Birmingham director of 3i, said the group's decision
to invest 'will help to accelerate other components of the financial
package'.
Leyland Daf has 100 acres of land, but Mr Ogilvy warned that 'it is not easy
to see a windfall' given the state of the property market.
He had talked to 'one or two people', but could not see any sign of
immediate speculative buying.
