<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Cost of artificial joints is criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'FASHION TRADE' in joint replacements is costing the National Health
Service many millions of pounds each year, research in the British Medical
Journal claims today.
Manufacturers, say the researchers, encouraged surgeons to believe that 'new
improved' expensive implants used to replace hips were better than
conventional cheaper models. Yet they were sometimes less satisfactory.
Health service implants are manufactured by about a dozen companies, many of
them US-based. Although British prices have been lower than elsewhere in
Europe and the US, they have risen recently.
The researchers, from the John Radcliffe Hospital and Nuffield Orthopaedic
Centre, both in Oxford, and Birmingham Orthopaedic Hospital, claim that
while a 'perfectly satisfactory' hip replacement could be marketed for about
Pounds 100, prices in the UK vary from Pounds 250 to more than Pounds 1,000.
Knee-replacement joints costing about Pounds 300 to manufacture were selling
for between Pounds 700 and Pounds 1,500.
About 40,000 hip-replacement operations a year are performed in Britain.
Many hospitals, says the report, have stopped replacing joints this
financial year because they have run out of money. The report says this is
'most unsatisfactory when cheaper hips are available and waiting lists are
so long'.
Long-term clinical results over 10 years showed that failure rates of some
of the cheapest models on the market were less than 1 per cent a year.
</TEXT>
