<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Amstrad launches 'Pen Pad' product
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMSTRAD, the consumer elec-tronics company, yesterday announced the first of
a family of 'personal digital assistants', hand-held electronic notebooks
which recognise and accept their owner's handwriting.
It can also be used to send faxes over the telephone network when connected
to a modem.
Designed by Amstrad and manufactured in mainland China, the 'Pen Pad', which
weighs under a pound, will be in high street shops by early May for Pounds
299.99 including value added tax.
It is not the first of its type, because Japanese and US companies are
already marketing hand-held computers which recognise handwriting.
Some of the world's largest electronics companies see a bright future for
such electronic notebooks and are planning their own versions.
The list includes IBM, AT&amp;T and Apple. Their products are expected to be
more sophisticated than Amstrad's version, although much more costly.
The Amstrad launch is an indication that the company, which recently
returned to profitability, is still capable of producing new product ideas.
Mr Sugar failed in December to persuade shareholders to sell him the shares
he does not already own, saying he could see no prospect of a 'blockbuster'
product on the horizon.
</TEXT>
