<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Six face arrest in Efim fraud inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROME magistrates yesterday issued six arrest warrants in connection with a
fraud inquiry into the activities of the finance subsidiaries of Efim, a
state holding company which was placed in liquidation last July.
The six included Mr Giuseppe Carrapico, a well-known Rome businessman and
owner of Rome football club, and Mr Mauro Leone, the son of the former
Italian president Giovanni Leone and former deputy chairman of Efim.
The arrest warrants were based on a string of fraud charges related to the
activities of Efim's financial services arm, Nuova Safim and its factoring
and leasing subsidiaries, Safim Factor and Safim Leasing in which BNL, the
state-controlled commercial bank, had a minority state until 1991.
The charges centre on alleged irregular leasing contracts for old people's
homes and health clinics, as well as alleged false billings for the supply
of equipment and services.
The investigation came to light last September, shortly after Efim had been
placed into liquidation with debts that are now known to be close to
L18,000bn (Pounds 8.21bn). Safim Factor and Safim Leasing have subsequently
been placed in liquidation as a result of the fraud enquiry. The extent of
losses suffered by Nuova Safim as a result of the fraud has not been
disclosed but it is understood to have been considerable.
At the same time yesterday, the Italian parliament agreed to waive the
immunity of three deputies from Naples accused of vote-buying in last
April's general election.
The three are Mr Francesco Di Lorenzo, the Liberal who resigned last month
as health minister, Mr Alfredo Vito, a Christian Democrat party boss and Mr
Giulio Di Donato, the leading Socialist in Naples.
Both the latter two deputies were yesterday advised they were under
investigation for alleged kick-backs in the privatisation of Naples rubbish
collection.
