<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Surprise fall in unemployment: Pound rises sharply as
figures boost hopes of economic recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT fell last month, for the first time in nearly three years. The
unexpected decline sent the pound sharply higher yesterday and raised hopes
that recovery is taking root.
The number of people out of work and claiming benefit fell by a seasonally
adjusted 22,000 in February. The drop was the biggest since November 1989
and kept the unemployment total below the politically sensitive 3m mark.
The Department of Employment said there was no obvious explanation for the
fall, which confounded City expectations of a 35,000 month-on-month
increase.
While welcoming the fall in unemployment, Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment
secretary, greeted the news cautiously. 'It would be consistent with
previous recoveries for the figures to be volatile for some time,' she said.
In the House of Commons, Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, said
he feared the February fall was a 'freak'.
'We are delighted if there are fewer people officially out of work. We hope
it will continue for future months and years. But we do fear it is a freak,'
he said.
Unemployment now stands at 2.97m, compared with 2.99m in January, while the
unemployment rate has dropped from 10.6 per cent to 10.5 per cent. The
unadjusted total dropped 19,451, but remained just over 3m.
Neither the government nor independent economists were willing to read too
much into one month's figures, but the fall added to evidence that interest
rate cuts over the past few months have stirred economic activity.
Building societies, meanwhile, reported that the value of new commitments to
mortgages rose 40 per cent last month, and earlier this week there were
encouraging retail sales and manufacturing output figures.
Prospects for a UK recovery were given a further boost by the Bundesbank's
decision to cut its discount rate by  1/2 a point, providing a more
favourable environment for lower European interest rates.
The fall in unemployment took the currency markets by surprise and the pound
immediately rose 2 pfennigs against the D-Mark. Sterling later closed in
London at DM2.44, up a net 2 1/2 pfennigs on the day and 5 1/4 pfennigs on
the week so far. The pound also rose sharply against the US dollar, gaining
nearly 2 1/2 cents in London to close at Dollars 1.475 and closing later in
New York at Dollars 1.486.
February's drop in the jobless total reflected a reduced number of people
becoming unemployed, rather than a higher number finding jobs or joining
government schemes which take them off the register. Trends still show a
steady increase in the jobless total which is expected to carry on rising
for the rest of this year. The February figures, however, suggest a slowing
at least in the rate of job losses. In the six months to February, the
average monthly rise was 26,700, marginally lower than the 27,700 in the six
months to January.
Mr Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, said the unemployment
and mortgage commitments data suggested that the economy was improving.
'It appears that the large rises in unemployment towards the end of 1992
reflected a final shake out by companies in order to get their cost base
under control, rather than a new downtrend in orders and output,' he said.
