<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Life industry to fight OFT plan for rule changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RULES for selling life insurance now in force 'have significantly
anti-competitive effects' and chief aspects of them should be changed, the
Office of Fair Trading ruled yesterday. The chancellor of the exchequer must
now decide whether to implement the OFT's proposals, which the life
insurance industry has vowed to fight.
The OFT urged that independent financial advisers be required to disclose
commissions in cash terms to prospective customers. It also said that
companies should be obliged to:
Tell prospective customers the surrender value of a policy in each year up
to its maturity date.
Use their own charges - and not industry average costs - when illustrating
to prospective customers what their likely returns will be.
Allow low-cost sales outlets, such as building societies, to price their
products more cheaply than other higher-cost agents.
The Association of British Insurers claimed the OFT's proposals would deter
consumers from buying life assurance products, and tilt the balance from
independent brokers in favour of banks and building societies.
Mr Brian Richardson, chairman of the ABI's life insurance council, said:
'There is a very real danger of overkill by regulation and excessive
disclosure which could add significantly to the insurance industry's costs
for very little real consumer benefit'.
Consumer groups, however, greeted the report with enthusiasm. Ms Jean
Eaglesham, head of money policy for the Consumers' Association, welcomed it.
She said: 'The fact that it has taken OFT intervention to provide firm
official support for the Consumers' Association's line reinforces our call
for statutory regulation of the financial services industry. Only then will
investor interests be adequately protected.'
The recommendations follow a year-long review of disclosure rules proposed
by the Securities and Investments Board and the self-regulatory bodies for
the retail financial services industry.
The life insurance industry has faced intense criticism since a SIB report
last year revealed that, in 1990, 37 per cent of unit-linked life policies
and 23 per cent of with profits policies were abandoned within two years.
Criticism was so great that last month the ABI mounted a public relations
campaign, as 'media representatives have attacked the industry by drawing
attention to high surrenders, poor surrender values, apparent high
commissions and expense costs'. The OFT's plans would require more
disclosure in all these areas.
Under the Financial Services Act, the OFT must determine whether the
self-regulatory bodies sufficiently promote competition. The OFT yesterday
also issued a report outlining what it believes are rules necessary to
protect investors.
Insurers attack 'unfair' disclosure demands, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
