<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Extra help with fuel bills as Major bows to backbenchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of a backbench revolt yesterday forced Mr John Major, the prime
minister, into promising extra help for 10m people on low incomes who will
be hit next year by the Budget imposition of value added tax on domestic
fuel and power.
The move marked a climbdown from earlier indications by Treasury and social
security ministers that compensation would be limited to uprating
income-related benefits in line with retail prices, including fuel costs.
The announcement eased alarm among Conservative MPs but the government
difficulties could be further deepened by separate official calculations
showing that hidden costs of government energy saving schemes could add
nearly 4 per cent a year to domestic fuel and electricity bills, in addition
to VAT.
Last night, there were no figures on how much the package announced by Mr
Major will cost - underlining the haste behind the move. Estimates
circulating among Tory MPs suggested the sum could be as high as Pounds 1bn,
which would have to be found from the public spending total already set for
1994-95.
The government was careful not to promise full compensation for the VAT
extension. It indicated that falling gas prices and the extra boost given to
benefit claimants this year would be taken into account. VAT on domestic
fuel will start at 8 per cent in April 1994.
Details of relief may not be decided until November - unless, as seemed
likely last night, pressure from Conservative MPs forces further
concessions. Some Tories are still pushing for an increase in the basic
state pension. The finance bill will be published immediately after the
Easter recess.
Amid complaints that the government's position had been 'misinterpreted',
the cabinet agreed for Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, to give
interviews to clarify the position. On Wednesday, Mr Michael Portillo,
Treasury chief secretary, appeared to rule out special help above price
indexation saying 'all such issues are made up of swings and roundabouts'.
Yesterday's decision will help 5m people on income support and a further 3m
on housing benefit, council tax benefit or family credit. Cold weather
payments will also be adjusted.
In the Commons, Mr John Smith, Labour leader, accused Mr Major of
'betraying' election promises by extending VAT.
Mr Major did not challenge Mr Smith's calculation that the 'typical' family
will have to pay Pounds 8.50 a week in extra taxes from next April and
Pounds 12.50 a week extra in the following year. But he said: 'I said last
year that we had no plans to raise taxes and nor did we. But we have an
overriding commitment to return the deficit to balance and to take the
action necessary to do that.'
Hidden 'green' costs, Page 6
</TEXT>
