<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER fell back from its highs during late LME trading as selling bore down
on the market. Resistance emerged around Dollars 2,210 a tonne for
three-month metal, which represents the ceiling of the current Dollars 40
trading range, and the market eased back to end at Dollars 2,198, still up
Dollars 20. The market's strength reflected widespread buying interest,
linked to supply-side concerns. Zaire's political situation is
deteriorating, there are labour problems at Chile's Chuquicamata and recent
falls in Comex stocks suggest output losses in Arizona early this year might
be larger than initially thought. GOLD edged back above Dollars 330 a troy
ounce on the London bullion market, but appears stuck in its current range
between Dollars 326 and Dollars 333. 'There has been some short-covering,
but it was capped by producer selling,' one dealer said. In New York raw
SUGAR prices were on the rise by midday on renewed technical buying and
continued sentiment that world supply is tightening.
Compiled from Reuters
