<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / International Company News: Bronfmans sell Trustco
subsidiaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TORONTO'S Bronfman family is parting with another of its major businesses by
selling Royal Trustco's operating subsidiaries to Royal Bank of Canada
(RBC).
RBC has agreed in principle to pay CDollars 1.65bn (USDollars 1.32bn) for
the operations, which include mortgage and other lending, institutional and
personal trust services, and investment management. Royal Trust had assets
of CDollars 134bn under administration on December 31.
The deal, which is subject to regulatory and shareholder approvals, will
increase RBC's corporate assets by about CDollars 14bn, or 10 per cent. The
bank, Canada's biggest financial institution, had assets of CDollars 137bn
on January 31.
Trilon Financial, a Bronfman holding company which owns 47.5 per cent of
Royal Trustco, said it would back the RBC offer. Trilon had initially
proposed selling only part of its Royal Trust stake and contributing to an
equity injection.
Royal Trust was put up for sale after suffering heavy losses. These stemmed
partly from the impact of recession on its core home mortgage business in
Canada, but mostly from a costly acquisition spree in the US and Europe in
the late 1980s.
The value of its assets hasbeen written down by almost CDollars 900m in the
past three years, and Royal Trust has either closed or sold almost all the
foreign businesses which it bought in the 1980s. It continues, however, to
own the UK-based Royal Trust Bank.
Royal Trust said yesterday that it suffered a 1992 loss of between CDollars
850m and CDollars 900m.
Under the agreement, Royal Trustco will retain CDollars 4.3bn of loans,
about one third of them in the UK, and about one quarter non-performing.
Prior to the Royal Trust sale, the Bronfman group had raised more than
CDollars 2bn this year from the sale of controlling stakes in, among others,
MacMillan Bloedel, the Vancouver-based forestry company, and John Labatt,
the brewing and entertainment group.
Mr Allan Taylor, RBC chairman, said yesterday that the acquisition of Royal
Trust advanced 'by several years' the bank's expansion strategy. Canadian
banks have been allowed to acquire trust and insurance companies only since
mid-1992.
RBC said it would finance the purchase partly through the issue of
non-cumulative preferred shares, which qualify as tier one capital under BIS
guidelines. It said it expected to have a tier one capital ratio 'in excess
of' 6 per cent when the deal is closed. Its ratio now stands at 6.7 per
cent.
</TEXT>
