<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Shopacheck boost for Cattle's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CATTLE'S (Holdings) reported a 27 per cent increase in pre-tax profits for
1992, mainly as a result of the continuing strong performance of its
consumer credit business.
Profits increased to Pounds 12.4m (Pounds 9.8m) on turnover lower at Pounds
217.8m (Pounds 244.7m) mainly reflecting the flotation of a 55 per cent
stake in Rosebys, the curtain and linen stores group, early last year.
The core consumer credit division, led by Shopacheck, the door-to-door
weekly credit business, increased profits to Pounds 12.3m (Pounds 9m) on
turnover of Pounds 167.1m (Pounds 154.8m).
Mr Eddie Cran, chief executive, said the gain highlighted the
rationalisation benefits following the acquisition of Compass Credit at the
end of 1990. He added that the charge for bad debts fell 'despite the
difficult economic background'.
The insurance services division lifted profits to Pounds 800,000 (Pounds
600,000) while the hire purchase and leasing division reduced losses to
Pounds 1.1m (Pounds 1.5m) despite a continuing high level of write-offs and
increases in bad debt provisions reflecting the problems of its small
business customers.
The group has reduced its non-core activities, selling the Indoor Leisure
Centre at a small loss in December and reducing the size of the retail video
film hire and travel agency businesses and charging closure costs agains
profits.
Rosebys' contribution to pre-tax profits as an associate was Pounds 1.1m
last year compared to Pounds 2.2m in the previous year when it was a wholly
owned subsidiary.
The disposal realised a surplus of Pounds 4.6m, of which Pounds 3.2m was
transferred to reserves in respect of goodwill previously written off, and
Pounds 1.4m was credited to the profit and loss account as an extraordinary
profit.
Earnings increased to 7.82p (6.13p) per share; a recommended final dividend
of 2.6p lifts the total for the year from 3.8p to 4.7p, including a special
distribution of 0.5p.
</TEXT>
