<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 93 / Spring Ram falls on profit warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPRING RAM, the kitchens and bathrooms company which was once a stock market
darling, lost half its market value yesterday as it warned that 1992 pre-tax
profit would be a third less than expected.
The company said the pre-tax figure would be not less than Pounds 26m, down
from a restated Pounds 36.2m in 1991. Analysts had predicted Pounds
37m-Pounds 40m. The share price fell from 129p pre-Wednesday's suspension to
63 1/2 p yesterday, valuing the company at Pounds 232m compared with its May
1992 peak of Pounds 651m.
Spring Ram's announcement followed haggling with its auditors over the
implementation of more conservative accounting principles. Questions about
the company's financial controls and accounting methods have undermined its
credibility before, most spectacularly last November when false accounting
was revealed at its Balterley Bathrooms subsidiary.
Yesterday's announcement listed Pounds 12.9m of deductions to the pre-tax
profit figure that the group would have announced under its old methods.
The biggest item was Pounds 5.6m of profits that the group had planned to
take in 1992 but which had to be pushed back. Analysts expressed unease
about this and were confused by the explanation that it was due to a draft
accounting standard.
Some shareholders suggested that Mr Stuart Greenwood, finance director,
should resign. Calls for the group to appoint non-executive directors were
reiterated. Mr Bill Rooney, chairman, said yesterday the group planned to
appoint two.
The profit shortfall was due to new accounting standards. The group was
surprised that so many companies had reported under FRS 3 before the
deadline and had only recently decided to follow. Pre-tax profit grew from
Pounds 1m in 1982 to Pounds 37.6m, before restatement, in 1991, on turnover
of Pounds 194.2m. The results are to be announced on Monday.
Details, Page 18
</TEXT>
