<DATE>930318
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Polly Peck administrators fail in court move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 17-MONTH attempt by Touche Ross, the administrators of Polly Peck
International, to sue the Central Bank of Turkish Cyprus for Pounds 45m was
rejected yesterday by the Court of Appeal.
The claim was part of the attempt by the administrators to recover between
Pounds 400m and Pounds 500m which was allegedly misappropriated from the
collapsed fruit and electronics group.
Touche Ross had claimed that the bank had knowingly assisted Mr Asil Nadir,
the former chairman of Polly Peck, in committing an alleged fraud or had
received the Pounds 45m knowing that it was being paid in breach of Mr
Nadir's fiduciary duty to Polly Peck.
Mr Nadir was alleged to have used the bank as a conduit through which Polly
Peck's money was diverted to 'friendly' hands in Northern Cyprus and
elsewhere.
Touche Ross had been given permission by the High Court to issue a writ
against the bank in Northern Cyprus, outside the jurisdiction of the UK
courts.
Three Appeal Court judges ruled yesterday by a 2-1 majority that the case
against the bank was not strong enough to justify allowing the writ to be
served in a foreign country.
Touche Ross said afterwards that it would be seeking leave to appeal against
the decision by the judges in the House of Lords.
Last year the Court of Appeal refused Touche Ross a Mareva injunction to
freeze Pounds 29m of assets held by the bank.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Polly Peck International.
</CO>
