<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / World Trade News: US pressure for managed Japan trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW voice yesterday joined the swelling US chorus demanding a form of
'managed trade' with Japan to counter that country's massive trade surplus
with the US.
Mr Derek Shearer, designated deputy undersecretary of commerce for economic
affairs, told a conference organised by the Economic Strategy Institute that
the administration should 'junk' the structural impediments initiative, a
key element of President George Bush's Japan trade policy, and negotiate
'results-oriented' import agreements, with targets for individual sectors.
The prestigious Advisory Committee for Trade Policy and Negotiations last
month recommended negotiating 'temporary quantitative indicators' with Japan
 -that is, a series of specific trade goals along the lines of the current
semiconductor agreement. President Bill Clinton expressed interest in the
approach when he later met members of the committee.
The consensus developing in Washington is for negotiated Japanese market
shares for sectors in which free market forces are blocked by formal,
structural or cultural trade barriers.
This would avoid Japan 'bashing', strengthen interdependence and recognise
that most US trade problems are 'made in America'.
Mr Shearer, a former Clinton campaign adviser, said the administration had
not yet had time to develop an international economic policy for the
post-cold war world. However, its Japan policy had to recognise that
'Japanese capitalism is different'; the US ought to be 'humble' about its
capacity to change Japan in the way the Bush administration had tried
through the structural impediments initiative.
'We need a results-oriented policy, but one in the context of a global
partnership,' he said. Japan should be fully involved in the attempt to help
Russia because its expertise and capital were badly needed. US-Japanese
co-operation was also required as regards China.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Balance of trade.
