<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont under fire from Brown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GORDON Brown, Labour's shadow chancellor, yesterday said in the Commons
that the government had betrayed the British people by breaking election
pledges not to increase taxation.
He told Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, that he would 'never be trusted
again'. Neither, he said, would the Tory party so long as it was led by Mr
John Major, the prime minister.
Mr Brown challenged Tory backbenchers uneasy about the extension of VAT to
domestic fuel and power to join Labour MPs in voting against the new impost
at the end of the four-day Budget debate.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, was ridiculed by
Labour MPs when he argued that the betrayal charge could not be sustained.
He claimed it had been made clear that if it became necessary to raise
revenue - 'and no government can rule out that possibility for all time' -
it would be done by extending the scope of taxation and not by raising rates
of tax.
Earlier Mr Brown called on Mr Lamont to say whether he had mentioned the
likelihood of increases in VAT and National Insurance contributions in his
personal election address.
While volunteering to make a rare intervention on the second day of the
Budget debate, Mr Lamont ignored the question.
Brushing aside Labour jibes, he challenged Mr Brown to say whether the
criticisms he directed at the government should also apply to France which,
with a Socialist administration, also had 3m unemployed, and to Ireland and
Spain, where, in percentage terms, unemployment was at a similar level.
Mr John Townend, MP for Bridlington and chairman of the Conservative
backbench finance committee, had less difficulty than the chancellor when Mr
Brown asked if he had promised his constituents there would be no increase
in taxation. 'I talked about no increases in direct taxation,' he said.
The Budget was welcomed by Mr Michael Brown, Tory MP for Brigg and
Cleethorpes, who underlined his confidence in Mr Lamont by saying he should
present not only the November Budget 'but the one after that in particular'.
Amid jeers and mocking laughter Mr Brown likened the significance of the
chancellor's proposals to the measures taken by Sir Geoffrey Howe in 1981
which 'won' the 1983 election for the Conservative party and 'sowed the
seeds' for the 1987 triumph.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
