<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / International Company News: United completes Boeing talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Airlines, one of the three large US carriers, said yesterday that it
had completed negotiations with the Seattle-based Boeing company over
reducing deliveries of new aircraft, although talks with engine
manufacturers were continuing.
The talks have been closely watched because United is a launch customer for
Boeing's new 777 wide-body jet, and there have been fears that these orders
might be affected.
United declined to comment on what reductions had been agreed, beyond
repeating that the cutbacks would be 'significant'. But Mr Julius Maldutis,
airline analyst at Salomon Brothers, told clients yesterday that United
would probably reduce orders by 29 aircraft next year, and by 28 in 1995.
United is scheduled to meet analysts today.
A Boeing spokesman would not give details of the negotiations but said the
results had been 'fully factored' into the reduced rate of production it
announced in January.
Meanwhile, American Airlines said that it planned to ground 25 McDonnell
Douglas DC10 aircraft between June and the end of 1993 - about half its DC10
fleet. The Dallas-based airline estimates that this will reduce its capacity
in the domestic marketplace by around 3 per cent in 1993 and by about 6 per
cent on an annualised basis.
In the wake of the extremely difficult domestic airline market condition,
the carrier has talked recently about reducing some of its less profitable
operations in the the US. There has also been speculation for many months
that American, one of the big three US carriers, may eventually reduce the
number of domestic hubs which it operates.
American stressed yesterday that it would continue to operate its fleet of
newer Airbuses.
</TEXT>
