<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Letter: Budget whittles away at pensions and penalises with
ACT changes (2)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Miss JENNY NELDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, What the chancellor did not say in his Budget speech, but should have
done, was: 'Some of our multinational companies have a problem with surplus
advance corporation tax. I propose to help them at the expense of the
shareholders of all UK companies by reducing the latter's gross dividends by
6.25 per cent. In addition to helping those multinational companies, I shall
benefit by some Pounds 1.2bn per year.'
One hopes that the need to help the Treasury and the multinational companies
concerned will be appreciated by:
1) those who do not use up their personal allowances and who will face a 20
per cent-plus fall in their tax rebates on dividends;
2) higher rate taxpayers whose higher rate tax on their net dividends will
rise by 25 per cent; and
3) employers whose pension funds will require larger contributions to
compensate for the reduction in their gross UK dividend income of 6.25 per
cent.
Jenny Nelder,
Bruce Sutherland &amp; Co,
Moreton-in-Marsh,
Gloucestershire GL56 0AT
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
