FT  18 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel 4 currently has a splendid Thursday night schedule. Tim Hunkin
(whose naturalness and lack of eccentricities contrasts so pleasantly with
the Loyd Grossman school of presenters) demonstrates the workings of
machinery in The Secret Life Of ..turning today to the photocopier (8.30).
When that ends at 9.00 the estimable Mary Goldring offers us The Goldring
Audit. Her subject today is British Telecom, and she finds that, nine years
after privatisation, Britain's largest company remains uncom petitive,
overmanned and bureaucratic. Then, at 10.00, comes Drop The Dead Donkey the
very funny series set in a television newsroom. What with this, One Foot In
The Grave, The Golden Girls, Red Dwarf and Waiting For God we seem to be
going through a period of classic comedy. Steve Humphries' series about
child rearing in the first half of this century, A Labour Of Love is proving
what a fascinating combination archive film and live reminiscence makes
(9.30 BBC2). In Disguises (9.30 ITV) reporters go undercover with fox
hunters and hunt saboteurs to report from both sides of the divide.
