FT  18 MAR 93 / Technology: Word for word in Japan - Worth Watching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japanese commuters could soon find a new way of buying their railway
tickets. Gone will be the man behind the counter and the push button ticket
machine. In their place will be a computer which recognises spoken requests.
This is just one scenario envisaged by NEC for its voice recognition system
which will be marketed in Japan this year. The machine can be programmed to
recognise 1,000 words which are relevant to each particular application.
The machine uses a technique developed at NEC's media research laboratory in
Kawasaki, called demi-syllable speech recognition. Each syllable is
dissected and analysed. NEC: Japan, 03 3798 6520.
</TEXT>
