<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / After the Budget: Caterer tastes what Lamont has served up -
Fleet expenses have soared for one company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN COMMON with businessmen across the country, Mr Jerry Brand was discussing
the Budget with his finance director yesterday. Mr Brand, managing director
and founder of Russell &amp; Brand, a five-year-old contract catering company,
was driving to his company's Leicester office as he spoke on his car phone
with Mr Simon Newth, the finance director. In Beckenham, south-east London,
Mr Newth was working out the detailed implications.
The most immediate impact of the chancellor's changes will be on the
company's car policy. The company, which turned over nearly Pounds 15m last
year, has a fleet of 65 cars, used mainly by its salesmen and contract
managers for visiting the schools, hospitals and businesses which are it
customers.
Mr Newth calculates that the increase of 12p a gallon on unleaded petrol
will cost the company just under Pounds 8,000 in 1993, while increased
employer's national insurance contributions on car and fuel benefits will
cost a further Pounds 4,000. A total increase of Pounds 12,000 represents a
sizeable chunk of the company's 1992 operating profit of Pounds 220,000, he
says.
There will have to be changes in our car policy, says Mr Brand, though his
options are limited. The company has considered the idea of giving employees
a cash benefit and allowing them to choose their own cars, but is worried
about the implications for the company image if they use unsuitable or
unreliable vehicles.
Staff could be given smaller cars, although many spend a great deal of time
in them on company business. There are limits to the discomfort they could
be expected to endure.
The second most significant issue to emerge from the Budget was the
announcement of plans to subsidise the return to work of up to 100,000 of
the long-term unemployed.
In a fast-growing industry with a shortage of skilled staff, Mr Brand
wonders whether he might take on employees under this scheme. He has his
reservations about the bureaucracy which might be involved, however, since a
proposal put to British Coal at the end of last year to retrain redundant
miners for catering work appears so far to have come to nothing.
'If the long-term unemployed fit in, then we are willing to have a look at
them,' says Mr Newth. At present, the company has a total workforce of about
1,250 people, most of them working in its kitchens. It has plans for rapid
expansion, however, and is projecting turnover this year of Pounds 21.5m.
Growth at this speed would mean taking on between 300 and 400 new people a
year.
Mr Newth welcomes the chancellor's decision to limit increases in business
rates to the rate of inflation. The company moved into a new head office in
Beckenham last December, doubling the size of space in use. This is expected
to lead to a sharp increase in its rate bill which will be about Pounds
31,000 this year.
But it is not only the direct impact of the chancellor's moves which will
affect the company. Mr Brand is also concerned about the impact of the
changes on its customers. If they decide to spend less of their incomes on a
hot midday meal, this may mean school and factory kitchens become less
viable.
Almost as important as the decisions taken by the chancellor in his Budget
were the changes he did not make. Mr Brand was looking closely at what the
chancellor would do to VAT. At present the Vatman regards catering companies
as agents providing labour to their customers and labour costs are not
therefore subject to VAT. The VAT authorities have, however, discussed
removing this concession although lobbying by the contract catering industry
has so far kept them at bay. 'If the VAT man taxed labour without letting
schools reclaim VAT, this would add enormously to their catering costs,'
says Mr Brand.
As Russell &amp; Brand has grown, the company has had to take more seriously the
implications of the annual Budget, says Mr Brand. The full implications of
Mr Lamont's decisions will become more apparent in the coming weeks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
