FT  18 MAR 93 / After The Budget: TUC gives welcome to job subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRADES Union Congress took the unusual step yesterday of welcoming some
employment measures in the Budget, including the use of job subsidies to
encourage employers to take on the long-term unemployed.
The TUC described as 'hopelessly inadequate', however, the larger package of
special employment measures which will provide 100,000 jobless people with
work experience or learning opportunities at a net cost of Pounds 125m.
Training and Enterprise Councils - which deliver government-funded training
schemes in England and Wales - will administer two of the four pilot job
subsidy programmes. They gave the government's move a guarded welcome.
Several Tecs already sponsor similar schemes and reward employers for
offering training and employment to the jobless.
One Tec chief executive said: 'If this initiative is developed and used more
widely we may find it more difficult to persuade employers to provide
training in return for a subsidy. If they get a subsidy for just giving a
person a job they may not be as eager to provide training.'
The Budget initiative that was given the warmest welcome was 'Tec
Challenge', a scheme in which Tecs are invited to come forward with new
ideas for tackling unemployment. Some Pounds 25m will be available for
projects.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, has asked a special
committee of Tecs to prepare ideas to tackle unemployment. It is expected to
report in June.
