<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / After The Budget: Company cars' change of direction likely
to pick up speed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMPOSITION of UK car sales is expected to change following the
simplification of company car benefit tax, Britain's volume car makers said
yesterday.
Mr Tony Brigden, director of fleet sales for UK market leader Ford, said
company car users were likely to seek voluntary 'downsizing' of vehicles to
lower individual tax bills.
'But this trend was in progress anyway through a general desire for smaller
cars and environmental factors, so all that the new scheme will do is
maintain this pressure,' Mr Brigden said.
More important was the removal of the current regime's combination of engine
capacity and price bands. 'Manufacturers can plan without having to take
account of false restrictions, and product planning can be driven wholly by
market forces,' he said.
Company car tax is based wholly on a percentage of cars' retail list prices
plus 'extras'. Car manufacturers, however, expect little negative effect on
sales volumes.
Companies at the lower end of the luxury and specialist sports car sectors,
such as Jaguar and TVR , are likely to welcome the new structure, to be
introduced next year.
Rolls-Royce and Aston Martin, however, which both sell cars in the Pounds
100,000 plus category, stand to be badly affected by the fact that there is
no 'ceiling' on the new tax scheme. The user of a 'perk' Rolls-Royce Silver
Spur costing Pounds 115,000, and covering fewer than 2,500 business miles,
will pay tax of Pounds 16,100 for the private benefit of the car under the
new scheme. This is based on paying tax at the top marginal rate on 35 per
cent of the retail list price of the car.
Under the existing scale charge system, entering its final year next month,
the charge will be only Pounds 6,024 - the same as for private use of a
Jaguar, or any other car costing above Pounds 29,000. Under the new system
the owner of a Pounds 33,600 Jaguar XJS, for example, will see his tax bill
reduced from Pounds 6,024 to Pounds 4,704.
Rolls-Royce expressed its dismay at the absence of any 'cap' on the tax
scheme and said it was 'considering what action we might take' between now
and the scheme's introduction.
Jaguar, wholly owned by Ford, said that 'in overall business terms it will
be very helpful to us in the UK market'.
It has been disadvantaged by the sharp increases in taxation accompanying
the two price thresholds of the current system - at Pounds 19,250 and Pounds
29,000 - and has had to produce 'tax break specials' in a not very
successful effort to compensate. Now it, too, expects to be able to
rationalise its model range and production.
In particular, Jaguar expects an end to the practice of cars being ordered
without extras, even air conditioning, so that the list price can be brought
under the tax threshold.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3711 Motor Vehicles and Car Bodies.
    P5012 Automobiles and Other Motor Vehicles.
    P5511 New and Used Car Dealers.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
