<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / After the Budget: Effect on consumer spending uncertain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS ARE under the fiscal equivalent of the sword of Damocles. How much
heed people pay to the Pounds 16bn of tax increases over a two-year period
from April next year will make a big difference to the pace and timing of
any sustained recovery.
The balance of opinion among economists and experts in consumer behaviour
yesterday was that Mr Lamont's fiscal tightening would act to depress
consumer spending in the year ahead.
Professor Peter Abell, a sociologist at the London School of Economics,
said: 'From a psychological point of view, the prospect of tax rises is a
damper. It will reinforce the air of despondency that many people feel after
the economic shocks of the past two years.'
The chancellor is gambling that by choosing a range of methods to raise
extra revenue the effects will be little noticed. The measures include
imposition of VAT on domestic fuel, higher national insurance contributions
and a freeze on income tax allowances.
Mr Lamont hopes also that the economic forces already prodding Britain in
the direction of an upturn will have had their full effect by the time the
tax rises take place.
Whatever their impact, the rises will serve as a highly practical test of
economic theories about 'rational expectations' - the idea that people and
businesses will adjust their behaviour in the light of all available
information, including the prospect of extra strains on their finances.
One sceptic is Mr Dan Elliot, an economist at PA Cambridge Economic
Consultants, a consultancy specialising in consumer behaviour. He thinks
rational expectation does not stand up when the information presented to
consumers is relatively diffuse and technical. As a result, the announcement
will have little impact on consumer spending, which accounts for about two
thirds of total UK output.
'In a few weeks, people will have forgotten about the tax rises,' said Mr
Elliot.
Another apparent sceptic is Mr Lamont, who said yesterday he thought the tax
rises would have no lasting effect on consumer confidence ahead of their
implementation.
Even so, the Treasury's economic projections published with the Budget
statement indicate that consumer activity will remain extremely weak over
the next nine months.
The Treasury reckons consumers' real, inflation-adjusted disposable income
will grow by only 0.75 per cent this year, after a relatively high 2.3 per
cent last year.
On the Treasury view, consumers will be prepared to save less of their
incomes, as confidence grows. It reckons the savings ratio - personal
savings as a proportion of disposable income - will fall from 11.4 per cent
in the final quarter of last year to just under 11 per cent next year.
But even with this prospect, the Treasury thinks consumer spending will rise
only slowly. It is predicting growth in spending of a modest 1.25 per cent
this year, after a 0.25 per cent rise last year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
