<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / After the Budget: Gambling to lose extra Pounds 15m a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY will get an extra Pounds 15m pay-out from gaming machines this
year as a result of the budget's 20 per cent increase in licence duty.
Licences for amusement-with-prizes (AWP) machines rise from Pounds 375 to
Pounds 450 a year - the fee for jackpot machines goes from Pounds 960 to
Pounds 1,150 a year.
The increases dented industry optimism, which was raised just a few weeks
ago by Home Office approval for higher prizes paid by one-arm bandits. Top
prize for the 190,000 AWP machines in operation, many in pubs, was lifted to
Pounds 3 cash or Pounds 6 in tokens. The jackpot limit for 35,000 machines
in private clubs was raised to Pounds 200.
Mr Paul Duckett, marketing manager for Associated Leisure, one of the
industry's big three suppliers, said: 'We had expected the higher prizes to
give the trade a useful fillip. The licence increase is a big
disappointment.'
The British Amusement and Catering Trade Association had urged the
chancellor not to increase the licence duty, saying that the industry had
absorbed the VAT increase two years ago and suffered from lower consumer
spending during the recession.
Mr Lamont's only concession was to abolish the duty from November 1 on
small-prize machines, which cost 5p to play. These account for about 5 per
cent of the total. The move is designed to help seasonal operators at
seaside sites.
</TEXT>
