<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / After the Budget: How ACT will affect companies . . .
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
HOW ACT WILL AFFECT COMPANIES. . .
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                              UK earners         Big overseas earners
                           Before    After    Before     After     FID*
                          (pds m)  (pds m)   (pds m)   (pds m)  (pds m)
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pre-tax profits
 from UK operations           100      100       100       100      100
 from overseas operations     100      100        20        20       20
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Net dividend                 25.0     25.0      25.0      25.0     25.0
ACT on dividend               8.3      6.3       8.3       6.3      1.3
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Gross dividend               33.3     31.3      33.3      31.3     26.3
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
UK corporation tax charge    33.0     33.0       6.6       6.6      6.6
Surplus ACT                   nil      nil       3.3       2.3      nil
Total UK tax paid            33.0     33.0       9.9       8.9      6.6
 as % of UK profit            33%      33%       49%       45%      33%
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: FT                                    * Foreign income dividend
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
How ACT works: Companies currently pay ACT on dividends at the rate of 25
per cent of the gross dividend, in future at 20 per cent. At the current
rate a Pounds 25m net dividend gives rise to Pounds 8.3m of ACT and a gross
dividend of Pounds 33.3m. When the move to the 20 per cent rate is complete,
a net dividend of Pounds 25m will give ACT of Pounds 6.3m and a gross
dividend of Pounds 31.3m. ACT is then offset against mainstream UK
corporation tax.
The first company, which earns all its profits in the UK, sees no change in
its total tax bill, but gets a cashflow benefit as Pounds 2m of tax switches
from payment in advance to arrears. However, a tax exempt investor will
receive a lower tax credit on its dividend.
The second company is unable fully to offset its ACT liability against its
UK corporation tax. Under the current system it takes Pounds 33 of
corporation tax to relieve Pounds 25 of ACT, leaving it with surplus ACT of
Pounds 3.3m. The change to the rate in the budget makes this worse, only
Pounds 20 of ACT can be offset against Pounds 33 of corporation tax.
However, the lower rate more than compensates and the surplus ACT reduces to
Pounds 2.3m.
If the foreign income dividend scheme is introduced, making dividends paid
from overseas profits free of ACT, the company's problem is solved. The
illustration assumes the company opts to pay 80 per cent of its dividend out
of foreigh profits. However, the tax-exempt investor is even worse off, as
it can only reclaim tax on the proportion of the dividend paid from UK
profits.
'I am pleased that the changes have come about, although the pension funds
are disadvantaged. I think they are strong enough to withstand the measures.
I think it is too early to say whether that means we will pay additional
dividends.'
Derek Bonham, chief executive of Hanson, who believes the Anglo-US
conglomerate's tax charge will fall by about Pounds 35m
'The changes will unquestionably be of use to us over the next few years.
But they will be of less help than one might think. There could be a problem
from tax-exempt shareholders pressing for higher dividends. T&amp;N has a
surplus ACT of more than Pounds 5m.'
Colin Hope, chairman and chief executive of T&amp;N, the motor components and
engineering group
'It is not clear our tax-exempt shareholders will be pressing for higher
dividends. We will make up our minds as to what we do after we hear back
from them.'
Peter Clappison, finance director of BBA, the automotive, aviation and
industrial component maker, who expects his group to save around Pounds 1m
in tax.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
