<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Summer start pledged for business
advice shop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST of the govern-ment's new one-stop business advice centres will
open in the summer, with a fresh round of bids for contracts to run them to
be invited this autumn, MPs were told yesterday.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, made the announcement as
he praised Tuesday's Budget for being full of 'very considerable' good news
for business.
He clashed with Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, over the
leaked DTI report showing a depressing outlook for British manufacturing.
Calling for publication of the document Mr Cook said it represented 'an
appalling verdict' on 14 years of Conservative government.
Mr Heseltine retorted that the report revealed the 'devastating inheritance'
the Tories had taken on in 1979 'when this country's economy was perceived
as the sick man of Europe'.
The confidential report concludes that UK industry is beset by weak
management and products and under-investment in new technology.
In the first round of applications to run 15 pilot one-stop outlets which
the government hopes will start the process of revolutionising support for
British companies, the Department of Trade and Industry received 57 bids.
The 'shops', which will eventually number 200, will bring together the
business services of chambers of commerce, local authorities, local
enterprise agencies and the DTI.
