<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: BAe chief urges aerospace strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG plea for a 'national strategy' for the aerospace industry was made
yesterday by Mr Dick Evans, chief executive of British Aerospace.
He told the Commons trade and industry committee that aerospace was one of
the few activities in which Britain was genuinely still a world leader. But
it was clear that France, and more recently Germany, had developed strategic
plans for their aerospace sectors.
'Unless we address the issue of investment in a much more specific way we
are in danger of losing the ground, or part of the ground, that we are
currently occupying,' he said.
He welcomed what he called a 'gratifying' improvement in the level of
dialogue between the industry and government. But Mr Evans said the industry
was relying on the Department of Trade and Industry to take the lead in
setting out a strategy.
With other companies, BAe is awaiting a response from ministers to proposals
for a national strategic technology acquisition plan, drawn up by a mixed
working group of civil servants and industry representatives.
Proposals include measures to fund work on different areas of aircraft
technology, including helicopters, and related activities such as air
traffic management.
Last year's US-European agreement limiting direct support for development of
new civil aircraft had halved the amount of launch aid that could be given.
Mr Evans described the accord as 'an extremely good agreement for the
Americans and an extremely poor agreement for the Europeans.'
Mr Mike Turner, BAe's regional aircraft chief, said the company would look
to the government to help with investment on the next regional jet and
turboprop aircraft projects.
