<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tory revolt looms over Budget VAT
move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT faces an all-party Commons inquiry into the impact on the
poor of imposing value added tax on domestic fuel, amid signs that the
Budget change could trigger a backbench Tory revolt.
The social security committee is expected to launch next week an
investigation into whether extra payments promised by the Treasury will
cover the increased burden on low-income households.
Unease surfaced among MPs as Mr Michael Portillo, the Treasury chief
secretary, refused to commit the government to compensate pensioners or
people on low incomes in full for the impact of VAT.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced on Tuesday that VAT will be
charged at 8 per cent on domestic fuel and power from April next year and at
17.5 per cent from April 1995.
Mr Portillo sought to rely on the pledge in the Budget statement that the
increase in bills would be taken into account when income-related benefits
were uprated in the autumn through a formula based on the retail prices
index. But, under pressure from Labour, the limits of that pledge became
more clear as Mr Portillo emphasised that in some instances people on
income-related benefits were over-compensated for price rises which in
practice affected them very little.
The Treasury estimates that the extension of VAT to domestic fuel will raise
the retail prices index by less than 1 percentage point.
A cross-party committee inquiry would heighten the political row over the
Budget. Mr David Shaw, the Tory social security committee member who
demanded the investigation, said: 'If something so sensitive comes up in the
Budget, we have got to look at it.'
Social security ministers believe that the Treasury will not agree to an
increase for all pensioners which fully reflects the impact of the VAT
change. Instead they are expecting some form of targeted payment which would
not apply to all the 9.9m who receive the basic retirement pension, but
would go to people on income support and on family credit.
Mr Andrew Bowden, Tory chairman of the all-party group of MPs campaigning
for pensioners, said on ITN yesterday that it was 'no use just increasing
the income support rate. There has got to be an increase in the basic
pension for all pensioners.'
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, last night wrote to Mr John Major
seeking confirmation that people on income support would be compensated in
full.
Downing Street was unworried yesterday by the Tory backbench reaction, but
the discontent could give the government cause for concern when the finance
bill implementing the Budget is considered in detail.
</TEXT>
