<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Beckett's vote reform move is
disallowed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S working party on electoral reform is edging closer to recommending
a change in the voting system in spite of a rearguard action by Mrs Margaret
Beckett.
A meeting of the group disallowed an attempt by Mrs Beckett, party deputy
leader, to revoke an earlier decision not to file a menu of options.
It reaffirmed the view of its chairman, Lord Plant, that it must deliver a
firm recommendation to the National Executive Committee when it meets next
month.
As Mrs Beckett, a passionate advocate of the present-first-past-the-post
voting system, cannot be seen to table a minority report, the odds seem now
tipped in favour of a recommendation for change.
Nonetheless, the committee is still divided over what system would be
appropriate, with its 16 members split into three groups. Probably the
largest of these - about six or seven-strong - supports a mixed-member
voting system.
This would reduce the total number of constituencies from 651 to 500, but
would further add 150 MPs selected by regions on the basis of candidates'
performances as 'best losers' in the election. The MPs would emerge as a
result of weighting the total number of MPs to reflect the parties' shares
of the vote.
The second grouping - somewhere between three and five-strong - supports
first-past-the-post. The last group favours a supplementary vote system that
ensures each MP is elected by an outright majority through a variation in
the alternative vote system.
The final decision of the committee, due at the end of the month, must be
passed for approval to the NEC before going out to consultation in the party
before the annual conference in September.
</TEXT>
<XX>
