<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Birt has reluctant support from BBC staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS DUNKLEY and GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN BIRT may have won the support of the BBC's board of governors in the
controversy over his tax affairs and employment terms. But how the affair
will affect the director-general's relations with the corporation's staff,
many of whom have expressed deep distaste for his management style and
proposed reforms, remains to be seen.
Some of his critics have, inevitably, hoped that the incident would bring
about his downfall and replacement by 'somebody whom programme makers could
relate to and follow, so that perhaps we would actually understand what was
going on', as one documentary producer put it.
Yet to judge by conversations with staff across the organisation yesterday,
this may be a minority view. Although their personal sympathy for Mr Birt
and his methods is limited, many concede that the BBC's interests will be
best served by his remaining in office. To a large extent, this view
reflects the belief that any alternative would be even worse.
'He pretty well has to stay. He's the fountain head of the only plan we've
got,' said one radio producer. 'If he went and (chairman Marmaduke) Hussey
went too, the BBC would face its gravest crisis ever.'
He also dismissed as unworkable the idea favoured by some staff that Mr John
Tusa, popular head of the World Service, should be appointed
director-general, backed up by Mr Bob Phillis, recently recruited from ITN
as Mr Birt's deputy.
'The trouble is that Phillis has never worked for the BBC before, and
however popular Tusa would be with staff, you couldn't really expect him to
take over the Birt plans with much conviction,' he said.
None of Mr Birt's innovations has been more controversial than the
introduction of Producer Choice, a system of market discipline and
budgeting. Intended to improve efficiency, it is seen by critics as an
attack on the BBC's creative resources. Yet some BBC rank and file were
arguing yesterday that the system, which has been widely viewed as a way of
cutting the organisation down to size, might actually be one of the most
solid guarantees of independence. a member of the drama department at
Television Centre said: 'Whether or not even Birt believes in Producer
Choice, it seems to be effective in keeping the government off the BBC's
back.'
Although Mr Birt may be winning staff support by default, the BBC governors
have won no plaudits for their handling of the controversy.
There is a widespread belief in the organisation that someone should be made
to pay the price for the affair by resigning - and that that person should
be Mr Hussey.
</TEXT>
