<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Names reject 'success fees'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of Lloyd's Names with heavy losses yesterday decisively rejected
proposals to award success fees to representatives organising legal action
on their behalf.
The Names, who are among more than 3,000 members of Gooda Walker syndicates,
also voted overwhelmingly to remove Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg and Mr Paul
Marland, the Conservative MP for West Gloucestershire, from the committee of
the Gooda Walker Action group.
Both Mr Marland and Mr Doll-Steinberg, the former chairman of the group, had
requisitioned a special general meeting of the action group in order to win
approval for the principle of success fees and to reduce the size of the
com-mittee.
At an occasionally stormy meeting more than 500 Gooda Names - individuals
whose assets support underwriting at Lloyd's - offered support for Mr
Michael Deeny, the current chairman who is a rock concert promoter, and nine
other committee members including Mr Tom Benyon, the former Conservative MP.
Mr Raymond Nottage, deputy chairman, said that it was necessary to put the
issue of remuneration for committee members on to the 'back burner so that
we can concentrate on getting ahead with litigation'.
Mr Marland said success fees were necessary to attract well-qualified people
to join.
More than 2,000 Gooda Names are seeking to recover Pounds 394m in insurance
losses in the largest legal action at the Lloyd's insurance market.
Gooda Walker syndicates specialised in catastrophe reinsurance business  -
covering the losses of other Lloyd's syndicates and London companies. Its
losses between 1987 and 1990 are calculated at more than Pounds 900m.
On average Gooda Names face losses of more than Pounds 185,000.
Writs naming 67 Lloyd's members' agents were served earlier this month.
Mr Doll-Steinberg claimed that he had been 'ousted' as chairman and said the
committee would become 'immune from the concerns of the action group'.
He added: 'My main concern has nothing to with receiving remuneration. There
has been a serious breach between the committee and the group.'
