<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Britons' foreign holidays surge to record level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent and ROLAND
ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH took a record number of foreign holidays but fewer vacations
within the UK last year, in spite of the recession and a campaign by the
English Tourist Board to promote seaside resorts.
The number of foreign holidays of four nights or more taken by UK residents
rose by 9 per cent to 21.75m, a survey published yesterday by the British
Tourist Authority shows.
This is the highest number recorded, and compares with the figures of 14.25m
in 1982 and 8.5m in 1972.
The number of UK holidays of four nights or more fell 6 per cent to 32m.
This compares with more than 40m in the mid 1970s.
Holidays in the UK represented 60 per cent of all holidays taken by British
residents last year, compared with 70 per cent in 1982 and 82 per cent in
1972.
The survey found that holidaymakers aged 25-34 and 55-64 are taking fewer
holidays at home. The authority said that 50 per cent of all British
holidays were spent at the seaside.
The average expenditure on a holiday abroad last year was Pounds 547. The
average expenditure on a British holiday was Pounds 140.
The West Country was the most popular UK destination for British tourists,
accounting for 23 per cent of all holidays taken, compared with 24 per cent
in 1991. Scotland accounted for 11 per cent, down 2 percentage points on
1991.
Wales was also the destination of 11 per cent of British holidaymakers, the
same percentage as in 1991.
Fears of a disastrous season last summer in Devon were not borne out by a
review there, Roland Adburgham writes.
Visitor numbers to the county - in terms of tourist nights - fell by more
than 3m (or 5.4 per cent) to 30.4m last year compared with 1991.
The review, which will be submitted tonight to the county council's economy
and employment committee, says the further fall last year reflected a
nationwide decline in the industry brought about by the recession, fear of
unemployment and discounting on foreign holidays.
The worst-hit sector in Devon last year was self-catering, with the
exception of tented camping, which benefited from trading down to cheap
holidays. The review says: 'Surprisingly, the serviced sector in hotels and
guest houses held up well with only a 1.7 per cent decline, although this
has to be considered in relation to a worse performance in 1991.' Hotels
suffered badly in 1991 and the review suggests they did better last year
because rationalisation led to higher occupancy rates for those remaining in
business.
It says there is an urgent need for research, improved training, raising
standards and developing new products.
</TEXT>
