<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Democrat leaders defend budget plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Congress began debating President Bill Clinton's budget proposals
yesterday amid a last-minute struggle by Democratic leaders to preserve the
plan against pressure for more cuts in spending.
The leadership appeared confident of winning passage, in votes expected
today, of a budget resolution that would cut the deficit by a total of
Dollars 510bn (Pounds 359bn) over the next five years through a combination
of spending cuts and tax rises.
'There is a substantial majority within the caucus to enact the package,'
said Mr Thomas Foley, Speaker of the House of Representatives.
Some party leaders were concerned, however, about pressure from conservative
Democrats, especially in the Senate, for cuts in the Dollars 16.3bn
short-term stimulus package that Mr Clinton proposes as an accompanying
measure.
The budget resolution, which does not get into the details of which
programmes would be cut, has already been considerably modified from the
initial plan laid out last month.
Echoing public enthusiasm for a serious attempt to tackle the federal budget
deficit, members insisted on Dollars 63bn of additional spending cuts over
five years. The resulting plan is expected to cut the budget deficit to
Dollars 183.6bn in 1997, compared with a target of Dollars 206bn in the
Clinton plan and a forecast of Dollars 322bn if policies remained unchanged.
But details of the spending cuts would have to be debated in a later budget
reconciliation bill, when support might start to coalesce behind individual
spending programmes now pencilled in for cuts.
The House is expected to debate one or two substitute budget resolutions
offered by the Republican minority, as well as an alternative proposed by
the congressional Black Caucus, which would make deeper cuts in defence to
pay for increased spending in areas such as education.
It remained unclear yesterday morning, however, how many amendments the
powerful rules committee would allow to be brought up.
</TEXT>
