FT  18 MAR 93 / Seoul move on interest rate delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Korea's new government is delaying plans to deregulate most interest
rates until the second half of the year, writes John Burton in Seoul.
Mr Hong Jae-hyong, finance minister, said this was because deregulation
could increase interest rates and further slow economic growth.
He said the government might instead cut the central bank's key lending
rates for the second time in three months to stimulate the economy.
It will decide whether to deregulate interest rates after reviewing economic
growth during the second quarter.
