<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Squeeze on public pay likely for further year: Budget wins
mixed reception in parliament and markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government signalled yesterday that the harsh squeeze on public sector
pay would be extended to next year as Mr Norman Lamont insisted that fiscal
austerity offered the only route to an eventual recovery in its political
fortunes.
The warning came amid growing demands from backbench Conservative MPs that
the elderly and the low-paid be given higher benefits to offset the
chancellor's Budget decision to extend value added tax to domestic fuel and
power.
But during fierce exchanges with opposition parties at Westminster, Mr
Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the treasury, refused to guarantee that
those on low incomes would be fully compensated for the cost of the extended
VAT.
As the row over VAT and a fierce Labour attack on the government's 'broken
promises' overshadowed an otherwise supportive reaction for the Budget from
Tory MPs, senior ministers warned of the fresh battle over public sector
pay.
They said a new ceiling on all public sector awards would have to be imposed
in 1994-95 if Whitehall departments were to meet Treasury spending targets.
The ceiling would have to be 'very close to', if not below, the 1.5 per cent
limit already applied to 1993-94.
Nurses, teachers, police officers, and other public sector workers would
then face a further real cut in incomes just as the chancellor's deferred
tax increases - including higher national insurance contributions - began to
bite in 1994.
The political risks for the government were underlined last night by the
decision of the Fire Brigades Union to press for strike action in protest
against the present pay ceiling.
The public spending squeeze has been tightened by sterling's sharp
devaluation since leaving the European exchange rate mechanism, which has
forced the Treasury to raise its medium-term inflation forecasts.
That in turn means that small real increases in the so-called control totals
for Whitehall spending planned in 1994-95 and 1995-96 have been replaced by
a 0.25 per cent cut in the first year and a freeze in the second.
But in an upbeat assessment of the medium-term impact of his austerity
Budget, Mr Lamont said the squeeze on public borrowing through tight control
of spending and increased tax revenues would lay the foundations for a
strong recovery in the government's political fortunes.
Mr Lamont said that taken with last November's autumn statement the budget
had re-established the government's firm grip on economic policy. He denied
that the Conservatives had broken firm pledges given during last year's
election campaign.
Mr Lamont strongly defended the extension of VAT to domestic fuel as
essential to meet Britain's international obligations to reduce carbon
dioxide emissions.
But as the Commons social security committee prepared to investigate the
measure's effect on low income households, some Tory MPs warned they would
fight for a clear Treasury commitment to compensate fully those reliant on
state pensions and welfare benefits.
