<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Lamont leaves room for wider tax measures: Budget wins mixed
reception in parliament and markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the chancellor, warned yesterday that the government would
take additional fiscal measures if it thought these were necessary to reduce
the UK's public sector deficit.
He said his Budget announcement of plans to increase taxation by a net
Pounds 6.7bn in 1994-95 and Pounds 10.3bn in 1995-96 was 'a bold step'
towards removing the threat posed by excessive borrowing to economic
recovery.
But at a post-Budget press briefing, he declined to rule out a further
extension of value added tax in addition to his decision to levy VAT on
domestic fuel and power from April next year.
The chancellor said he regarded the Pounds 243.8bn 'control total' set in
November for government spending in 1993-94 as a ceiling, not to be breached
in negotiations between the Treasury and government departments ahead of the
unified Budget in November.
He said the next spending round would be influenced by the long-term review
of all aspects of government spending being carried out by Mr Michael
Portillo, chief secretary. Treasury officials confirmed that if this yielded
savings, the chancellor would use them to cut the deficit further.
Mr Lamont said he wanted the UK budget to move towards balance around the
top of the economic cycle. But he also said the Maastricht criterion
limiting the budget deficit to 3 per cent of gross domestic product was a
'good objective'.
The Budget predicts that the PSBR will increase to Pounds 50.1bn in 1993-94,
or 8 per cent of GDP, from Pounds 35.1bn in the current financial year,
about 5.75 per cent of GDP. It forecasts only a gradual decline to Pounds
30bn, or 3.75 per cent of GDP, by 1997-98.
Mr Lamont said he expected that most of the cyclical influences that had
contributed to the UK's large deficits would have worked through the economy
by the end of 1997. But he denied that this meant a large part of the
deficit was structural.
He said the 'vast majority' of the present PSBR was cyclical, reflecting the
effects of the recession such as high unemployment and reduced tax revenues
on the government's finances. He underlined that the PSBR projections were
subject to uncertainty and said they could prove pessimistic if tax revenues
were more buoyant than expected.
The chancellor said he had not wanted to lessen the prospects for economic
recovery this year in the Budget. However, he believed the main threat to
sustained recovery was excessive borrowing.
