<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 93 / Equities slip back but sterling gains: Budget wins mixed
reception in parliament and markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL markets continued to treat the Budget warily yesterday as traders
and investors struggled to digest its many complex elements.
Sterling again made modest gains against the D-Mark and the dollar as
currency investors were reassured by the chancellor's statement that the
level of UK base rates was appropriate to current economic conditions.
UK government bond prices also bounced back from the lows reached on Tuesday
as markets re-assessed the impact of the Budget and shrugged off the
chancellor's announcement that the public sector borrowing requirement for
next year would be around Pounds 50bn.
However, Mr Norman Lamont's decision to leave interest rate policy unchanged
triggered a small setback for share prices. Equities were unsettled as the
market tried to assess the impact of the government's planned changes to
advance corporation tax.
The share prices of many overseas-earning companies were particularly
depressed as their income may be affected by foreign income dividend
proposals. On the London stock market, the FT-SE 100 Index closed 29.4 down
at 2,889.9, although trading in shares was not heavy.
There had been some speculation before the Budget that Mr Lamont would
announce another cut in UK base rates to help stimulate economic recovery.
However, the pound's strength in recent days has also been triggered by a
growing belief in financial markets that the Bundesbank will ease its
important Lombard and discount rates at a council meeting today.
Sterling gained 1 1/4 pfennigs in London to DM2.4150, but eased in New York
to DM2.4136. Longer-dated gilts advanced as dealers expressed relief that Mr
Lamont had relaxed the full-funding rule to allow purchases of gilts by
banks and building societies to count towards the PSBR.
Gilts, Page 31
Currencies, Page 33
London stocks, Page 42
